<!-- 04 PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>
    <p class="lead">Every repair starts with a proper diagnosis, we identify the root cause, give you a written quote, then fix it. We don't replace parts on a guess.</p>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Standing Water After the Cycle</h3>
        <p>The drain pump is the first place we look, either the pump motor has failed or the pump filter and drain hose are blocked. On most dishwashers the filter is accessible from inside the tub. In SoCal's hard water environment, mineral buildup in the filter and pump is common and often the only issue. We clean before we replace.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Start / Door Won't Latch</h3>
        <p>The door latch assembly is one of the most frequent dishwasher failures across all brands, the machine won't run unless it confirms the door is fully latched. After latch: a failed control board, tripped thermal fuse, or a faulty door switch. We carry door latch assemblies for the major brands on the van.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Dishes Come Out Dirty</h3>
        <p>Three likely causes: clogged spray arm ports (mineral deposits blocking the jets, very common across SoCal), a failing wash pump not building adequate pressure, or a detergent dispenser not opening at the right point in the cycle. We check all three systematically. Sometimes it's as simple as clearing blocked spray arm holes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Dishwasher Leaking</h3>
        <p>A door gasket that's cracked, compressed, or has debris caught in it is the most common leak point, water escapes during the wash cycle and pools on the floor. A failed water inlet valve that doesn't shut off fully, a cracked spray arm, or a loose hose connection can also cause leaks. The source matters before anything is replaced.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Dishes Not Drying</h3>
        <p>On dishwashers with a heated dry cycle, a failed heating element is the usual cause, the element that heats the air inside the tub during drying burns out over time. On condensation-dry models (common on Bosch and Miele), the rinse aid dispenser level and the drying fan motor are the first things to check.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Cloudy Glasses / White Film</h3>
        <p>Almost always SoCal hard water, high calcium content leaves mineral deposits on glass over time. If the machine is running correctly but every cycle leaves white residue, the dishwasher isn't broken. We confirm the spray arms and inlet valve screen are clear, advise on rinse aid levels, and discuss whether a water softener additive makes sense for your water hardness.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Grinding or Rattling Noise</h3>
        <p>Grinding during the wash cycle usually points to the wash pump motor, a bearing or impeller issue. A loose or cracked spray arm hitting the dish rack produces a rhythmic rattling. We run a test cycle and locate the noise source before recommending parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Error Codes</h3>
        <p>Bosch, Miele, Samsung, LG, and Thermador dishwashers display specific error codes that point to the failed component. Our technicians are current on the diagnostic codes for the brands we service most across SoCal, these codes eliminate guesswork and shorten repair time significantly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 SOCAL HARD WATER -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, SoCal Hard Water &amp; Your Dishwasher</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The dishwasher issue most SoCal homeowners don't know about</h2>
    <p class="lead">Southern California has among the hardest municipal water in the country. That mineral content affects every appliance that runs water, dishwashers especially.</p>

    <div class="hardwater-block">
      <div class="hw-label">💧 Hard Water Effects Across SoCal</div>
      <h3>SoCal water is approximately 300–400 mg/L of total dissolved solids</h3>
      <p>For context, water above 180 mg/L is classified as "very hard." Most SoCal water supplies, sourced from the Colorado River, the State Water Project (Northern California aqueducts), and groundwater across all 5 counties, sit well above that threshold. Inland Empire wells (San Bernardino, Riverside) often run even harder. Every cycle deposits a small amount of calcium and magnesium on every surface the water touches, the spray arm ports, the filter, the heating element, the door gasket, and the tub interior.</p>
      <p>Over months and years, this accumulation reduces wash performance, causes premature component failure, and produces the cloudy glassware and white residue that SoCal residents accept as normal. It doesn't have to be. Our technicians descale spray arms and inlet valve screens as part of every dishwasher service call, and we'll tell you honestly whether the performance issue you're seeing is the machine or the water.</p>

      <div class="hw-signs">
        <div class="hw-sign">
          <strong>White film on glasses</strong>
          <span>Calcium deposits from every cycle, not a broken dishwasher</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-sign">
          <strong>Reduced spray pressure</strong>
          <span>Mineral deposits blocking spray arm ports over time</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-sign">
          <strong>Filter clogs faster</strong>
          <span>Mineral buildup combines with food debris, restricts drain flow</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-sign">
          <strong>Heating element failure</strong>
          <span>Scale coating on the element reduces efficiency and causes burnout</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-sign">
          <strong>Door gasket deterioration</strong>
          <span>Mineral deposits in gasket groove accelerate cracking and leaks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hw-sign">
          <strong>Water inlet valve clogging</strong>
          <span>Inlet screen fills with calcium, dishwasher fills slowly or not at all</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

