<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06, Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills (LA County) · Miele G7000 Panel-Ready</div>
        <h3>"Door won't close all the way, dishwasher won't run"</h3>
        <p>Door latch assembly failure on a Miele G7000. The latch mechanism had worn to the point where it wasn't registering as fully closed even when the door was shut. On a panel-ready unit the door panel has to come off before any latch work, the custom panel was a two-tone lacquer finish that had to be handled carefully.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Removed custom panel without damage, replaced door latch assembly with OEM Miele part, reinstalled panel and verified alignment. Machine ran a full cycle before we left. Customer mentioned the previous technician had told them the control board needed replacing, it didn't. The latch was the entire issue.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena (LA County) · Bosch 800 Series</div>
        <h3>"Dishes come out with grit on them, bottom rack especially"</h3>
        <p>Classic SoCal hard water presentation: spray arm ports on the lower arm were almost completely blocked with calcium deposits after years of use in Pasadena's hard water. The bottom rack dishes, closest to the lower spray arm, were getting almost no water pressure. The upper arm was partially blocked as well. The filter was also heavily coated.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Removed and descaled both spray arms with citric acid solution, cleared all jet ports, replaced the inlet valve screen which was 80% blocked, deep-cleaned the filter assembly. Full wash cycle confirmed good pressure throughout. Customer had been running a cup of vinegar in the machine monthly, helpful but not sufficient for the ports.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (Orange County) · KitchenAid KDTM604</div>
        <h3>"Water sitting in bottom every morning, wasn't always like this"</h3>
        <p>Drain pump failure, the impeller had cracked, likely from a hard piece of debris that made it through the filter. KitchenAid dishwashers across SoCal have this failure mode more often than they should because many owners don't realize there's a filter that needs regular cleaning, so debris load on the pump is higher. Coastal Newport Beach humidity also accelerates seal degradation on pump assemblies.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced drain pump assembly with OEM KitchenAid part, thoroughly cleaned the filter and drain sump (significant buildup), verified drain flow during a full cycle. Also showed the customer where the filter is and how to clean it, this is a five-minute task that extends pump life considerably.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura County) · Samsung DW80R5061US</div>
        <h3>"E3 code keeps coming up, stops mid-cycle"</h3>
        <p>E3 on this Samsung model indicates a water supply issue, the dishwasher isn't getting adequate water flow to begin the cycle. The water inlet valve screen was heavily clogged with mineral deposits from Conejo Valley's notably hard water supply (Calleguas Municipal Water District water runs harder than average, typical for the Ventura County corridor).</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced water inlet valve (the screen was past cleaning, valve was also running slow on flow rate indicating partial internal failure), cleared the sump inlet of secondary buildup. Error code cleared, tub filled to proper level, full cycle completed without interruption. Advised customer on monthly citric acid maintenance cycle.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

